content: Don't pay fo the Pro version version. The free one darkens up to 80% but the pro goes until 100%. replyContent: The 20% means both intensity and dim values combined. Otherwise, the screen would become too colored/dark that so it would be impossible to see anything if we allow users to put both on 100%. So, if you want dimmer try to decrease intensity a bit and you should get a better range of dim instead

App works, but there is one major flaw. I'm 100% positive it's this app due to the testing I've done. The issue is that it draws pretty much over the whole screen. Not a drawing, but an invisible later that prevents you from using pay apps such as Google Pay from within another app. Example- have the app running and order a Lyft ride and select Google Pay to pay. You cannot confirm the payment because a system notification pops is saying another app is drawing over the screen. You can circumvent this by pausing the Night Shift app, but this should not be necessary.
replyContent: Android system requires that filter is paused while operating on sensitive screens (like permissions, accessibility, etc.). It is not possible to detect this, so you have to pause the filter manually when "Overlay Detected" dialog appears, then close the dialog and finish the sensitive action.
